y: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/2/01 8:31:25 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#333333>(4/2/01 8:30:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Reaching down, a lithe hand grasped the morning grass, wet with dew, and slowly rose to sniff the sweetness of spring. Birds sang, hidden among the great boles of the forest while a doe darted in and out of sight, disappearing into the brush. Senses attuned to nature drank in the sights and smells, feeling at peace, as always. This was home. Kelethin, the great tree city of the wood elves, fashioned from love, sweat, and the blessing of Tunare.<br><br>Llerian, eldest of the Moonbow clan and one time ranger sat back against the mighty Oak and continued the task at hand. An arrow shaft, lovingly carved from the best wood lay in his fletching kit. The feathers of a hawk, carefully collected, were affixed to the shaft and would make the arrow fly straight and true, like the bird they came from. A small nock, made from bone, would grip the bowstring like a lover. And the last, a silver tipped head, imbued with the magic of Tunare so as to strike even creatures from the Netherworld. His hand absently brushed the long red locks of hair behind his upswept, pointed ears as he put the finishing touches onto the arrow<br><br>Suddenly, Llerian’s head snapped up. The usual sounds of the forest had gone strangely quiet. With the silence only a ranger could accomplish, the fletching kit was closed, a bow, the likes of which few have ever seen, was drawn out and strung, and an arrow nocked. Where before a craftsman had worked his craft now stood only empty space as Llerian disappeared into the foliage surrounding his home. Silence reigned.<br><br>A curse pierced the silence as a huge man tripped over a large vine and stumbled into the clearing surrounding Llerian’s small house. He was huge, standing close to seven feet tall and carrying a huge spear that seemed to be coated in slime. His much dented and worn armor shone a russet bronze in the shafts of sunlight let in by the overhead foliage. His helmet, crowned with the horns of some animal, came off his head as he wiped his brow free of sweat. From the blue tattoos that covered his face, it was now obvious that this was a Northman, often labeled barbarians, from the cold steppes of the Everfrost Peaks. His once young face was scarred by years of working the Art of the shaman. It is a hard life that takes its toll on any who practice it.<br>Without ceremony, he dumped his shield, which looked to have been through a roaring fire, so blackened and charred did it appear, onto the grass. Unslinging his water skin, he took a long pull and surveyed the small cottage.<br><br>“LLERIAN! Curse you for a flea ridden dog, where are you?!?”<br><br>Unnocking the arrow, Llerian stepped from around the trunk of an oak tree, “As usual you wake the dead with that bellow of yours Curghann Bearfist.”<br><br>The huge barbarian and the slender elf locked arms in greeting and after a moment, both grinned.<br><br>“How long has it been my friend?” asked Llerian.<br><br>Clasping Llerian around the shoulders, Curghann says, “Too long, and while I have become an old man, you stay as you have always been. Damn all elves! Come invite me into your fine home and we will share a meal.” Quickly picking up his gear, Curghann followed Llerian.<br><br>As they walked toward the small cottage Curghann appraised his elven friend. They entered the main room of the cottage and Llerian immediately went to the fireplace. Placing two fresh connies on the spit to roast, he set about preparing some wild tubers and carrots.<br><br>Glancing at the tall barbarian, Llerian said. “I know better than to think this is a social call. You detest boats and for you to travel the Ocean of Tears means something is afoot.”<br><br>Curghann simply glanced around the room, noticing the many fine bows that decorated the walls. He picked up Llerian’s longbow, the secret bow that only the rangers of Kelethin know how to make and even then, only master fletchers, and caressed the wood.<br><br>With a penetrating stare, Curghann said. “How long has it been since this bow hunted something more fearsome than a deer?”<br><br>The barbarian’s stern look was answered with an angry glare, as Llerian stopped his cooking. “You know my reasons for hanging up my swords.” With effort, the anger drained away and he resumed his chopping. Carrots and tubers were placed in the pot and hung over the fire. As he mixed in various spices and tree bark, he continued. “You can’t know what it was like, hanging there on those chains, watching the Teir’Dal preparing their evil rites.” In a whisper, his voice filled with remembered dread, he explained. “The servants of Najeena know their business well. When it finally came, I welcomed death. I knew I would join Tunare and know everlasting peace. But no, I was denied even that. If not for chance, I’d be there still, my soul trapped for all time. Snapping out of his memories, Llerian looked at Curghann, “Sometimes I wake at night, and I can still feel the chains on me, binding my soul to darkness.”<br><br>With a sigh, Curghann said, “The elven Lords have begun the colonization of Kunark. The clans of the North have promised aid and I have journeyed there to give what aid I may. Close to the outpost is a huge lake, once blue and filled with life, but now it’s waters run dark and it is home to foul creatures that plague the surrounding area. I need you ranger. I need your skills and your courage by my side. Goblins, more cunning and intelligent than the tribes I’ve fought before, patrol the lake and guard the entrance to an ancient city. The leader of these goblins, I believe, holds the key to the city and should we defeat him and gain entrance, we can learn much.”<br><br>As Curghann spoke, Llerian shook his head. “I will not go. The peace of the forest is all that keeps the demons I harbor from overwhelming me. I am sorry you wasted your time in coming here. Know you my brother, Llars, has become a powerful druid and serves Tunare well. Seek his aid for I will not leave here.”<br><br>A single tear, quickly brushed aside, fell down Curghann’s face. “Aye, I know it. It is why I sought you out. Llars already agreed to help me. But we failed. We were overwhelmed and with his last scrap of power he cast a Succor to take us away from that cursed lake. But when the spell faded and I could see again, he was not there. I knew not what had befallen.<br><br>“I found myself in the Butcherblock Mountains and immediately came to Kelethin to seek aid from the druid council. The Hierophant communed with Tunare herself to learn if Llars was at her side. He is not. He lives and can only be a prisoner of those thrice damned Bloodgills. The council said the majority of the Faydark Champions were already spread to thin between Kunark and the constant struggle with the Crushbone Orcs. Those they could spare were green to the ways of battle and would prove small help. Then one mentioned you. I had thought you still in Surefall Glade and rejoiced that you were here. Misplaced hope I now see.”<br><br>Gathering his weapons, Curghann made for the door. “The ranger I knew was filled with courage and a passionate rage and the ranger I see before me is an empty shell. You go through the motions of life but do not truly live. If you wake to feel chains binding you, they are of your own fashioning, made of fear and self-pity.”<br><br>Without a second glance, Curghann was out the door and into the forest, heading south toward the Butcherblock Mountains and from there, Kunark<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/4/01 1:37:42 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#333333>(4/2/01 8:39:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> One more for today <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>---<br><br>Llerian sat cross-legged before the fire, seeking that calm meditative state where he could find peace. His mind was filled with images of the dark priests of Najeena, fearsome goblins, and his brother. The images mixed and he saw Llars hanging in the dungeons of the Teir’Dal, trapped for all time. He saw them slowly take him down and toss him into a foul vat of dark water where hungry goblins waited. His usual peaceful mood would not come.<br><br>Slowly standing, tears streaming down his face, he crossed the room to the back corner. Carefully, he opened the secret compartment in the floorboards and hauled out a large chest. Taking a silver key that had hung around his neck for ten years, he unlocked the chest and opened it. He drew forth first his weapons, two short swords of the Ykesha, their power and craftsmanship long lost to the world, scavenged from the remains of an ancient and dead empire. He donned his mithril chain tunic, forged by the rangers of Kithicor, etched with ivy. Leggings of similar make covered his legs and jewelry from various adventures and pieces of scavenged armor quickly followed the ivy-etched mithril.<br><br>With a last look at his home for the past decade, Llerian drew a black vial from his belt pouch. Removing the stopper, he quickly quaffed the potion before his mind could dwell on the contents. He felt the magic course through his veins and he was off, running through the woods in the direction his friend had gone. Curghann had a few hours head start but no one of the Northland could navigate the forest of Faydark and the Butcherblock Mountains like one born to this region. Llerian was confident that he could catch his friend before the boat left.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/4/01 1:37:24 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(4/3/01 8:46:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Wow, tough crowd, lol. <p><BR><A HREF=http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=14097>Llerian Moonbow</A><BR>54 Pathfinder</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#333333>(4/3/01 2:20:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> The sun shone bright against the waters of the Ocean of Tears. It was a hot day for being so early in the season and Curghann drank deep from his water skin. A friendly dwarf maid was fishing off the dock and chatting idly with a young gnome. A swift breeze took much of the sun’s sting away, for which Curghann gave thanks. His heavy armor was uncomfortable on the best days and sweating inside of it only made it worse. But he wouldn’t trade it for all the gold in Norrath, for the magics placed on the armor by the totem spirits had kept him alive more times than he could count.<br><br>Off in the distance, he could see the great elven warship, Maiden’s Voyage, and the 4 small skiffs that would carry passengers to the ship. As the skiffs approached the dock, a voice next to him caused him to jump in surprise.<br><br>“After we rescue Llars, and recover this key you need, I am coming back”, said Llerian. The ranger looked straight out at the huge warship, avoiding Curghann’s eyes.<br><br>Curghann said nothing, merely nodded, and placed his hand on Llerian’s shoulder. Together, they boarded the skiffs that would take them to Maiden’s Voyage and Kunark and into the teeth of danger.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/4/01 1:38:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#333333>(4/3/01 2:25:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Rain lashed down and the waters of the small river leading away from the outpost were gorged as if from a full meal. The rocky terrain, made slick by the sudden storm, proved dangerous to cross. The two adventurers cautiously followed the river, the fog obscuring what little visibility would have been possible in the rain. Llerian stopped a moment, bending down to examine the ground.<br><br>Nearly shouting over the rain, Llerian said, “Tracks. Looks like goblin but none that I have ever seen before. And some kind of feline tracks as well.”<br><br>Curghann eyed the surrounding area, his spear held at the ready. “Aye, goblins are thick in these parts, like flees on a beggar’s ass. We should steer clear of them if we can. We have bigger fish to fry.”<br><br>Llerian stood up and continued to follow the river. For almost an hour they continued on, stopping frequently so Llerian could examine any tracks in the mud. The fog was beginning to lift and the rain had slowed to a drizzle. Occasionally, the roar of some wild beast would split the patter of the rain. Llerian glanced at Curghann, raising an eyebrow.<br><br>Curghann said, “Sabertooth.”<br><br>Llerian shrugged and continued on. For another quarter hour the light rain continued before finally ceasing all together. Llerian removed the oilcloth cover from his quiver and rubbed his longbow down, replacing the string with a dry one from his pack.<br><br>Curghann pulled a rough map from his pack and laid it against a rock, motioning for Llerian to take a look.<br><br>Pointing to a spot in the middle of the lake, Curghann said, “This is the ancient city I spoke of. It rests now on the floor of the lake. Guards are posted here, here, and here.” Curghann used a piece of charcoal to mark places on the map. Looking up, he pointed to a ruined stone tower in the middle of the lake. “There may be more guards at the base of that tower but I think we can avoid them.”<br><br>“Fair enough. Let’s get this over with,” said Llerian.<br><br>They crested the last hill and headed for the lakeshore. Edging around the shoreline, they passed a tall, ruined structure located on a hill to the right. As they were passing it, Llerian stopped, holding his hand out to Curghann. Bending down, he examined more tracks in the mud. As he made to rise, a war cry sounded and six goblins came sprinting around the structure, their loping gate eating up the distance between them and the two heroes.<br><br>Instinct took over and Llerian moved with the fluid grace that only an elf could manage. Arrow after arrow left his bow and struck with startling accuracy. The first arrow struck the lead goblin in the chest, blasting him backwards. The goblin directly behind him staggered over his fallen companion and lay still, stunned. The second arrow took another goblin in the thigh, while the third and fourth arrow hit the last goblin in the charge, one piercing its eye, killing it instantly.<br><br>Curghann reacted only a second after Llerian and intoning a spell in the language of the north, he summoned spirits from the Netherworld. The icy touch of the otherworldly spirits slammed into one of the remaining goblins. It collapsed, ice forming around its body as the spirits bled it of all life. The last goblin charged on, headless of the danger and angered beyond reason at the death of its kin. Tossing his bow to the side, Llerian leaped to meet the charge, his short swords working to deflect the razor sharp claws of the goblin. Each time the goblin tried an attack, Llerian would exploit the weakness of its attack and launch a counter attack. In seconds, the goblin was bleeding from many small wounds. Fear overcame its rage and it turned to flee, sprinting towards the ruined building. With careful aim, Curghann threw his massive spear, catching the fleeing goblin in the back, killing it.<br><br>The stunned goblin had recovered by now and launched an attack at the ranger. Claws raked his back but the ivy armor turned the claws away. Spinning, Llerian used brute force to smash the goblins arms out of the way with one swipe, partially spinning it. With a low thrust, he sunk his second short sword deep into the goblin's chest. Staring at the sword, the goblin slid off the blade with a piteous gurgle.<br><br>The goblin Llerian had wounded with arrows was making a vain attempt to crawl away, seeing its death in the ranger’s eyes. Llerian murmured a quick prayer to Tunare and the goblin suddenly tripped on a shrub. It once again tried to move away and a root snagged its ankle. Hampered, it clawed at the ground, desperately trying to flee. Llerian closed in and with a single stroke, ended the fight.<br><br>Llerian retrieved Curghann’s spear and handing it back to him, said, “The bodies?”<br><br>Curghann spit in disgust, and said, “Leave them. The scavengers will deal with it, I’ve no doubt. We’ve tarried long enough. Let us head down and see what we may. We will need your magic to prevent us from drowning. I will prepare us for battle.”<br><br>Curghann began casting, once again using the language of his birth. Llerian watched as Curghann summoned spirits of protection around both of them. He could almost see the spirits gather around him, and wondered at his friend’s power. Next Curghann removed a small talisman from his pack and holding it in both hands, began another spell. Soon, the talisman began to glow with a faint aura. Handing it to Llerian, he said, “This will offer some protection as well as the guardian spirits I summoned. Quickly now, cast your spell and lets head down.”<br><br>After Llerian had cast his breath spell, they waded into the water and Llerian could almost smell the evil. The water was tepid and rank. What horrible torture was being visited upon his brother in this place? With firm resolve, he pushed away his discomfort and dove into the lake. The murky water closed over them and they were gone.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http: