suddenly appearing in its chest. It was confused at why it couldn’t call out for help. But then it realized, when it saw the elf appear with a sword held high, that its throat had been cut. Death caught up to it then, and it died without a sound. Llerian made a few brief gestures and he disappeared, his magic making him blend in with the surroundings. Curghann cast a spell and he, too, disappeared. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/4/01 1:37:02 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#333333>(4/4/01 1:20:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Two goblins stood guard at the entrance to an ancient building. Its walls were covered with algae and barnacles; the once gleaming marble is faded and huge cracks run the length of it from whatever catastrophe created the lake and sank the city. A huge statue of a lizard man, a mute witness since the age when the city bustled with daily life, stands above the entrance.<br>Once again, Llerian appeared, but no attack came from the elf. Instead, he began a complicated spell and the two goblins were engulfed in a bright light. Their eyes glazed over and a leering grin covered their faces as if they understood a secret that they had long sought, but only just discovered. Llerian motioned and he quickly passed through the doorway and a ripple of water followed him.<br><br>But the ranger had made a mistake. The shadows in the entrance exploded into motion and a huge goblin, much bigger than the door guards, tackled the ranger. With the wind knocked out of him, Llerian was unable to draw his swords. The goblin’s claws pierced his ivy armor and the water was soon red with the ranger’s blood. Before he could recover, the goblin had pinned him down and was beating him senseless.<br><br>Once again, as Curghann appeared, spirits of ice slammed into the fell beast, knocking him off Llerian. He shrugged off the spell and launched himself at Curghann, howling in rage and pain. Curghann took the brunt of the attack on his shield but one claw connected and Curghann felt ribs snap, though his armor prevented a more serious wound. Curghann doubted he could survive a second attack.<br><br>Flames enveloped the huge monster as Llerian, recovered from the first assault, punished the goblin’s flank, driving him up against the wall with a blinding attack. His short swords moved in a blur, but this goblin was much more skilled than the others and he parried the short swords almost casually. Llerian cursed himself for those long years of idleness, which dulled his fighting skills, but he continued the attack.<br><br>Curghann completed a second spell and the goblin was racked with pain as venom seeped into his skin.<br><br>&quot;The spell I cast won’t last forever. If the other two join in, this will be all over,&quot; Llerian exclaimed!<br><br>Curghann responded with another spell, this one though aimed at the elf. Llerian felt the magic course through him and his weapons somehow seemed lighter, his opponent seemed to attack slower. Llerian began a steady rhythm, building on the goblin’s momentum like a dancer. Moments before the ranger was fully on the defensive, but now the tables had turned and the goblin was bleeding from many wounds. More icy spirits slammed into him and screaming in pain, he turned to the barbarian to crush the life from him. But that was the opening the ranger needed. With a double thrust, he pierced the beast’s back and with a vicious twist of his swords, severed the goblin’s spine.<br><br>Realizing their survival was measured in seconds, Llerian spat out another harmony spell on the door guards. Then with quick precision, he cut their throats.<br><br>Curghann slumped against the wall, exhausted. Glancing at his friend, he said, &quot;You did well elf. I thought that beast beyond us but you’ve a trick or two to be sure.&quot;<br><br>Llerian covered the bodies with sand as best he could and slumped down next to his companion. He murmured another prayer to Tunare and the spell infused his muscles, restoring lost energy. He cast the same spell on Curghann.<br><br>&quot;It won’t be long before we are discovered. We must press on. Are you ready?&quot; he asked.<br><br>Curghann nodded. Reaching down, he pulled a heavy chain from around the goblin's neck.  A dull, rusted key hung on the end of it.  Curghann grunted in satisfaction and slipped it around his own neck.  Two more spells were quickly cast and Llerian could feel his wounds closing slowly, the healing process greatly accelerated by the shaman’s spell. Curghann picked up his gear and they entered the fallen city.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/4/01 1:38:49 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#333333>(4/6/01 8:51:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Shadows danced around the underwater hall. Phosphorecent fungi coated the ceiling providing an erie light. A ripple in the water and the faint clank of armor was the only hint that something approached. Llerian and Curghann cautiously advanced, the ranger barely seen as he hugged the shadows. The hallway, though once straight, angled upward, the walls and ceiling showing cracks and part of the rocky lake floor had pierced the bottom, showing through the marble like the jagged teeth of some huge beast. After a 100 yards or so the hallway breeched the water and the two heroes stopped their advance. A small room with branching corridors loomed before them.<br><br>Llerian whispered, &quot;Which way?&quot;<br><br>&quot;I've no more knowledge of this place than yourself elf,&quot; Curghann replied.<br><br>&quot;Stay here then. I'll scout ahead. If you hear the cry of a hawk, come with all speed,&quot; said Llerian.<br><br>With that, the ranger disappeared into the shadow of the right hand corridor. Curghann backed up as much as he could into a huge crack in the wall, almost totally hidden, and sat to await his companion.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#333333>(4/6/01 8:53:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Llerian wiped sweat from his brow. The corridors of this fallen city were humid and rank. Years of algae and fungus grew thick on the walls, thriving in the moist air. The light given off by the fungi cast the rooms and halls with a sickly greenish tint. The faint clang, as if a hammer striking metal, could be heard ahead.<br><br>Llerian could see a dull red light coming from the far end of the hall. The wet floor made it almost impossible to move silently but Llerian hoped the sound of the hammer would mask any sound he might make. Peaking his head around the corner, the clang on the hammer grew very loud. A huge room opened up and Llerian could see a forge at the far end. A skinny lizard man, whom Llerian had learned were called Iksar, worked the forge. Various weapons were arrayed next to the forge and a huge goblin bent over a table where a finely crafted harpoon lay. The goblin began invoking some foul spell and the harpoon began glowling with a dull orange aura. It quickly faded and the goblin cackled with glee. Looking up, it noticed the Iksar smith taking a long gulp of water and snarling, it picked up a barbed whip and whipped the poor Iksar. It hissed something in its own tongue and stalked out a side passage.<br><br>The Iksar accepted its punishment without complaint and when the goblin left, Llerian noticed the lash wounds begin to close, without spell or gesture. As the smith turned back to the forge, Llerian ducked into the room and melded into the shadows. <br><br>Before the Iksar could continue his work, the blade of a sword came up to its chin. Its eyes went wide as the form of the elf appeared before it. Motioning with his head, Llerian drew the lizard man back into the shadows, keeping his blade firmly against the creatures throat.<br><br>Whispering, Llerian asked, &quot;Can you understand me?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Yesss elfling, I speak the tongue of the mans,&quot; it hissed, equally quiet.<br><br>Llerian nodded, &quot;An elf like me, dark hair, similar features. Where?&quot;<br><br>&quot;All soft skinss look the same elfling, to me. But he could only be where all prisoners are kept,&quot; it said.<br><br>The Iksar pointed down the hall where the goblin had gone, &quot;Down that hall, come to a big room, many goblinss. Passt that to the left is a pit where the prisonerss are kept. Down into darkness you must go to save your friend.&quot;<br><br>As suddenly as he appeared, the ranger was gone, down the hall where the goblin spellcaster had gone. The Iksar went to return to work when it noticed the harpoon the goblin had been working on was missing. Shaking its scaled head, it decided the stories the broodling masters had told it about elves being part demon must be true.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#333333>(4/6/01 8:53:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> A large fire burned brightly, the walls dripped with moss and algae turned the color of dried blood by the light. The once proud hall was a shambles. Years of goblin life had worn away any sign of what must have been a place where kings held court. The smoke of the fire was trapped by a mystical net on the ceiling, keeping the room fairly free of smoke, although the air was far from fresh. The stench of unwashed bodies, excrement, and burnt fish clung to Llerian like a wet blanket. He hid in a niche in the wall, totally obscured by shadow. The goblins mostly slept, with the occasional movement from one guard near the fire. Llerian had wiped some algae and mud on his face and hands to mask his scent, for he knew goblins had sensitive noses and would detect him no matter how silent he was.<br><br>Occasionally, he could hear the cry of a human or elf from the far end of the room and he cursed himself. There was no way to get to the opposite side completely undetected.<br>He counted five warriors sleeping and one standing guard, although the guard spent more time staring into the fire than watching for danger and Llerian knew that should he look up, it would be a few moments before his eyes adjusted.<br><br>A log split in the fire, throwing sparks and the guard jumped back with a start, crying out. Other goblins stirred, snarling at the guard in their own tongue. In the commotion, Llerian slipped out of the crevice he was in and moved silently down the hall, back to the forge.<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A> at: 4/6/01 8:54:22 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#333333>(4/6/01 8:57:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Curghann stirred from his meditations as a figure crossed the path of light coming into his hiding place. Standing, he brought his spear to the ready just as Llerian came into view.<br><br>“You took your time elf,” said Curghann.<br><br>Glancing over his shoulder, Llerian replied, “The path ahead is thick with goblins. I had to be extremely cautious to avoid detection. There is a forge down this corridor, with an Iksar smithing for the goblins. He is most likely a slave. Past him, quite some distance is the room where the prisoners are kept. That is where Llars is likely to be, though I couldn’t get close enough to see the prisoners. I double backed and looked around. The rest of the corridors are collapsed and without mighty magic or heavy labor, we cannot pass. There must be another way however because I saw no evidence of females or young. Unless there is another entrance from outside.”<br><br>Without looking back, Llerian slipped into the darkness once more, heading back towards the forge. Curghann followed as best he could. Something else slipped out of the crack and followed the proud barbarian and only the ripple of puddles on the floor marked its passage.<br><br>The lash sliced into the Iksar, opening another terrible wound on his back. The goblin snarled in hatred, and grabbing the Iksar by the throat, lifted him off the ground, crushing his throat. Unable to breath, the Iksar almost smiled as he felt the cold touch of death coming. Finally, he would be free.<br><br>A sword came down and severed the goblin’s hand at the wrist. The Iksar slumped down and the goblin cried out in pain. He turned toward his attacker and Llerian parried a clumsy blow.<br><br>“Looking for this?” Llerian snarled. He rammed the harpoon into the goblin’s stomach and twisted it savagely. The goblin clung to life and tried to cast a spell but Curghann’s spear took it in the throat and its last spell turned to a gurgle and it died.<br><br>Llerian bent over the fallen Iksar and saw that it was still alive. He incanted quickly and healing energy surrounded the lizard and a few of his wounds closed. As the Iksar stirred, Llerian picked up the chain around its neck and he could feel the tingle of magic. He dispelled the enchantment with a quick prayer and the chain collar split in two and fell to the floor.<br><br>“We’ve no time for this elf, the sound of the battle may have alerted the rest of the scum. Time is our enemy now.”<br><br>Llerian ignored the warning for he knew the Iksar was punished because he stole the harpoon. Llerian dragged the Iksar into the corner. The Iksar, now conscious, opened his eyes and nodded his thanks. “I will live. It wass worth the lassh to ssee that harpoon I crafted sstained by hiss blood.”<br><br>Llerian rejoined Curghann and they made their way down the hall leading to the prisoners. The trickle of water and the sounds of the forge helped to mask Curghann as his armor prevented him from moving quietly.<br><br>Llerian motioned for Curghann to stop. Looking around, the ranger saw no sign that any other creature was here. A puzzled frown crossed Llerian’s face. The trickle of water was undisturbed and the sound of the fire came from up ahead. Everything seemed normal but the ranger was still uneasy.<br><br>“I sense we are not alone, but I can’t place the feeling. Stay alert”<br><br>As Llerian turned to continue on, Curghann smiled and followed after. The air behind Curghann stirred ever so slightly as something followed after.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/umredsuperstar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MrEd Superstar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MrEd MiniTank!</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#333333>(4/15/01 3:52:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=13>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Nice stories... wish I had the time on my hands that you seemingly do  LOL <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>Good work <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><font size=3><font color=blue><b>MrEd Superstar</b></f><BR> <font size=2><font color=dark red><i>Gnomish Wizard<BR>Tinkerer Extraordinaire!</i></f></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.e