=6.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Darkness deeper than any he had ever known shackled his spirit. He faintly remembered another existence in which he did not feel constant despair. Others moaned softly near him, sometimes these others cried out in pain calling out to gods, lying in their own feces as he was. The air was thick, like molasses, and sweat drenched his naked form. He remembered something that felt good, it was cool as it went down his throat, but he could not name it. It was so long since the green skinned monster had brought some and his throat ached for it. His lips were cracked and dried blood coated his right side. How he came to be injured was a mystery to him but it hurt when he tried to move so he knew it was recent. He dreamed sometimes, of huge trees stretching up to the heavens. He heard voices, someone singing. Small ones, little ones, children, yes that was the name. Children. Laughter. Sadness. Love. He had a name once, though he couldn’t remember it now. There was a beautiful woman. He thought at first it was his mother, as some of the wretches here cried out for, but it wasn’t. She was young and ancient. She was innocent and wise. She was life and death. He knew it was important, but he couldn’t remember. As always, whenever he thought of her, the pain began, in his head. It would grow worse the more he thought of it. As always, he struggled as long as he could, trying to remember her. As always, the pain overcame his will and he passed out. <p><BR><A HREF=http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=14097>Llerian Moonbow</A><BR>55 Outrider<BR><BR>"This rudderless world is not shaped by vague metaphysical forces. It is not God who kills the children. Not Fate that butchers them or Destiny that feeds them to the dogs.  It's us.  Only us."<BR><BR>-Rorschach, The Watchmen</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tunare's Concubine</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/01 4:01:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> Llerian pointed and Curghann noticed the guard sitting by the fire. Apparently the sound of their previous battle had not carried this far but it would only be a matter of time before the goblin shaman was missed. Curghann indicated he would handle the guard by the fire and Llerian should head for the cell. Nodding once, Llerian drew his swords. He edged over to the entrance to the room and turned, awaiting Curghann’s signal. Curghann murmured a quick prayer and his eyes glowed violet.<br><br>Then, standing tall, he openly strode into the room and called out an ancient battle cry of the North. The goblin looked up for the fire, totally surprised and only saw a seven-foot monster of darkness. Raising its arms to cover its face, it cried out in fear, screaming something. Llerian wasted no time. He was darting in and out of the shadows made by the fire. He was halfway to the pit before the goblin recovered.<br><br>Curghann launched his attack, taking the goblin in the shoulder with his spear. Blood splattered the shaman’s armor and the goblin stumbled over a sleeping companion and then rose, its cries changing from fear to pain and anger. As before, Curghann called on the totem spirits. But instead of killing the goblin as he did outside, the spell hit the blazing fire. Ice met fire and a loud hiss like a thousand deadly snakes was heard. Steam erupted from the fire and scalded those goblins sleeping closest to the fire pit. Then the fire went out and the room was plunged into darkness.<br><br>Two warriors in the back leaped from their pallets and began advancing on the barbarian. Curghann's magic allowed him to see perfectly and he spat another spell, unleashing a killing rain of acidic poison on the advancing goblins. Blankets and tunics melted in the storm and skin blistered and burned. The goblins howled in agony. Before the goblins could attack, Curghann turned and sprinted down the corridor, his laughter echoing back. Moments later, five goblins darted after him.<br><br>The three remaining goblins snarled at each other, obviously unwilling to leave the room undefended. Whatever they said to each other was lost on Llerian, but he had already reached the pit and was half way down. Reaching the floor, the stench nearly made him vomit but he managed to control himself and quickly began searching the prisoners. Picking his way through blood, muck, and feces, he couldn’t believe the size of it. It stretched on for nearly fifty yards. Most of the prisoners were dead, mainly from starvation, but many groaned as he passed them. His heart ached to see these poor wretches but he knew he could not save everyone. His brother was his primary concern. He steeled his heart and pressed on.<br><br>With no warning at all, one of the bodies stood up and landed a stunning blow to his head. His ears ringing, Llerian tried to defend himself but his vision was blurred and he couldn’t make out where the attacker was. A second blow landed and the elf felt ribs crack.<br><br>Years of training took over and the ranger’s swords crossed in front of him, parrying an attack. He skipped out of the way, getting some distance to get his bearings. His vision focused and he saw the skinniest goblin he had ever seen. It was emaciated, almost a skeleton with skin. Around its neck was a necklace of humanoid tongues, and it had a belt made out of skulls. It was hunched over and moved more like an ape. Its fangs were yellow and broken and one of its eyes had been ripped out. Its tongue licked at the air, as if it sought to taste whether the elf was fresh enough for a meal.<br><br>Claws came down and Llerian dodged the first and parried the second, dancing to the side of the goblin. A lightning stroke opened a gash in the goblins side, which it barely noticed. It kicked out to the side, catching Llerian square in the chest. Hardly sure footed in the slime that coated the floor, Llerian slammed against the wall of the pit and fell to the floor. The goblin lifted the bruised ranger from the floor and hurled him against the opposite wall. It advanced, cackling with glee.<br><br>Tears of frustration and pain streaked down his cheeks. Trying to rise, he knew it was almost over. Looking back, he saw the goblin towering over him. <br><br>“Oh Tunare, I tried. Forgive me brother.”<br> <p><BR><A HREF=http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=14097>Llerian Moonbow</A><BR>55 Outrider<BR><BR>"This rudderless world is not shaped by vague metaphysical forces. It is not God who kills the children. Not Fate that butchers them or Destiny that feeds them to the dogs.  It's us.  Only us."<BR><BR>-Rorschach, The Watchmen</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ullerian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llerian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tunare's Concubine</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/01 4:03:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Llerian's Return</span><hr size=1> He cowered in terror. The green monster was throwing someone around the room. Sometimes it happened. A prisoner would cry too much or attack the terrible thing and it would kill. If he could somehow not be noticed, maybe he would live. He didn’t know why, but he wanted to live. He needed to live. He cried out as the monster threw the other one against the wall right next to him. He tried to quiet his sobs so as not to attract the monster’s attention.<br><br>“Oh Tunare, I tried. Forgive me brother.”<br><br>His eyes snapped open and he looked at the other. He saw pain etched on the other’s face. The other struggled to rise, carrying what he knew were weapons. He saw the pointed ears peeking threw long red hair. He reached up and touched his own ears, feeling the skin taper to a point. The other was like him. And he knew that word. It sang to him like a bird on the first day of spring. He sat up.<br><br>“Tunare.”<br><br>His heart knew joy. He knew that word. He knew her. Tunare.<br><br>“Tunare!!”<br><br>He launched himself at the monster. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bthecrossroadstavern8833.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=sabit>Sabit</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#333333>(4/27/01 2:03:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.3footwookie.com/jim13.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> /plead</span><hr size=1> More, more, more!<br><br>Dear god please! give us more!<br><br>This is the best story set in the EQ world I've read in a loooooong time. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href="http://216.207.128.204/Database/Characters.asp?Style=Wyld&ID=351">Sabit Pequeno</a><br>Gnome Cleric of the Horde<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap 